Q14_1: For each of your teammates and yourself, write one line that describes their primary contribution to the team's work together. You can certainly list technical contributions (e.g., great at Figma), but we also encourage more personal contributions (e.g., provided encouragement to me, wicked sense of humor, compassion, etc.) The list of individual skills may be useful in identifying other ideas. Include your own contribution as well, as it is the contrast between what you say and what your teammates say that provides insight. When writing your evaluation, be specific, kind, diplomatic and actionable. Avoid making general statements like "everybody was great" or "she's cool". Q25: The TeamingxDesign team is developing machine learning algorithms to process the responses provided in these teaming assessments. We aim to make these assessment and feedback processes increasingly helpful to your learning experience. We may share our findings in academic research papers to help other educators teach teaming. Before we analyze the data, we remove all identifying information, including your name and email, as well as the name of the class. We ask your consent to add your anonymized responses to the growing dataset of teaming data. Your choice to participate in the research or not WILL NOT AFFECT  your ability to finish class assignments, receive feedback from these assessments, or your grade in the class. If you have any questions, please feel free to contact Sara Beckman (beckman@berkeley.edu) or Krina Patel (pkrina1990@berkeley.edu).
